This article is a proclamation by President Barack Obama on the 25th anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). The ADA is a landmark civil rights legislation that ensures fairness, opportunity, and complete participation in all aspects of American life for individuals with disabilities. The proclamation recognizes the efforts and sacrifices made by countless Americans to pass the ADA and emphasizes the ongoing work to uphold the spirit and letter of the law. It highlights the unique challenges faced by people with disabilities and the commitment of the administration to address these challenges, including access to healthcare, affordable housing, financial institutions, and innovative technologies. The proclamation also emphasizes the importance of equal access, opportunity, and respect for all individuals and encourages Americans to celebrate the 25th anniversary of the ADA and the contributions of individuals with disabilities.